{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"abd2bb0a-7f6f-4fbb-882f-bc7db3172407","content":"This is a known breaking change. In .NET 10 MAUI, Android enables **edge-to-edge** rendering by default (Android 15+), so `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` no longer drives layout. You need to react to **IME window-insets** instead.\n\n### Fix — `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`\n\n```csharp\nusing Android.OS;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity\n{\n    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n    {\n        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n        // Let the app draw behind system bars; insets drive padding\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);\n\n        var root = FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;\n        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(root, new ImeInsetsListener());\n    }\n\n    private class ImeInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n    {\n        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(\n            Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n        {\n            var ime = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n            var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n\n            // Use whichever is larger: keyboard or nav-bar\n            v.SetPadding(\n                bars.Left, bars.Top, bars.Right,\n                Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom));\n\n            return insets;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Why this works\n\n| Old (.NET 9) | New (.NET 10) |\n|---|---|\n| `adjustResize` shrinks the window | Edge-to-edge: window is full-screen |\n| System handled layout shift | App must read `Ime()` insets and apply padding |\n\n### Also remove the old platform-specific call\n\nIf you have this anywhere, delete it — it's now a no-op:\n\n```csharp\n// ❌ Remove\nApp.Current.On<Android>()\n    .UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust(WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize);\n```\n\n### XAML layout tip for the chat screen\n\nUse a `Grid` so the input bar naturally sits at the bottom and the message list fills remaining space:\n\n```xml\n<Grid RowDefinitions=\"*,Auto\">\n    <CollectionView Grid.Row=\"0\" ItemsSource=\"{Binding Messages}\"\n                    ItemsUpdatingScrollMode=\"KeepLastItemInView\" />\n    <Entry Grid.Row=\"1\" Placeholder=\"Type a message…\"\n           ReturnCommand=\"{Binding SendCommand}\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\nWhen the keyboard opens, the insets listener adds bottom padding to the root view, pushing your entire layout up — the `Entry` stays visible above the keyboard.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"01262775-a5e5-48e4-a64a-a815d13e636c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue where the keyboard covers the text input at the bottom of the screen on Android. They mention that `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` no longer works in .NET 10 (which would be the upcoming version after .NET 9).\n\nThis is a known issue. In Android 11+ (API 30+), `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` was deprecated. .NET MAUI has been evolving its approach to handle this.\n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, you could use:\n```csharp\nApp.Current.On<Android>().UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust(WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize);\n\n\n```\n\nBut in newer Android versions and .NET MAUI versions, the recommended approach is to use the Android `WindowInsets` API and edge-to-edge display handling. For .NET 10 / .NET MAUI, this involves leveraging `AndroidX.Core` with `WindowCompat` and `WindowInsetsCompat` to properly manage insets, or relying on the edge-to-edge display support that MAUI has adopted by default in recent versions.\n\nThe key issue is that `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` was deprecated in Android API 30, and while `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` still works for older APIs, the modern approach uses the `WindowInsets` API instead. Since .NET MAUI now enables edge-to-edge rendering by default on Android, the app draws behind system bars, which changes how keyboard adjustment behaves. The practical solution is to use padding that responds to keyboard insets or leverage the newer .NET MAUI APIs for keyboard visibility handling.\n\n```\n\ncsharp\n// Platform-specific code to listen to keyboard insets and adjust padding\n```\n\nI'm also considering whether the MAUI community toolkit's keyboard behavior or the built-in keyboard handling in .NET MAUI 10 might provide a simpler solution.\n\nActually, thinking through this more carefully: Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`, so the modern approach involves keeping `adjustResize` in the manifest for partial compatibility, then using edge-to-edge mode with proper inset handling on the MAUI side. The practical solution is to structure the layout with a grid that has flexible and auto-sized rows, letting the keyboard push content up naturally.\n\nBuilding the XAML layout... Setting up the window insets listener... Finishing the insets listener logic...\n\nI'm realizing I should step back and think about what actually works reliably across platforms. For Android, the insets approach handles both the IME and system bars by taking the maximum padding needed. On iOS, the native behavior is generally better, though there might still be edge cases to handle. Given this is a CLI tool, I should focus on giving a practical, concise solution rather than getting bogged down in implementation details.","outputTokens":2442,"requestId":"D459:282C31:1C205A2:1FA396D:6A07BF91"},"id":"0a95920c-0da6-447e-8856-85cfc9958a7f","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:52:10.786Z","parentId":"2ca9fbf1-d7ff-4ec3-a100-4590d628dd72"}
